posts.com:
>TwentyFive Lighters - Dawning Blue EP
>April 2020
>vapor trap, phonk, neoclassical new age

A dreamy, ethereal EP from when the hexd scene was starting to explode. It is NOT hexd though. While it borrows some aesthetic elements from the movement, the music itself is almost the complete antithesis to the hexd style as it is slower with very clean sounding production and made with no samples. The beat style is rooted in southern hip hop while the soundscapes seem inspired by new age music.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=i0qUMat6PWA

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>Sacred Gateways - Shuffled Trance
>September 2020
>bubblegum dance, trance

Arguably Pulp's creative peak and most cult favorite album. It is a complete change in style from the earlier albums. It still has something thematic similarity though, like new age textures on songs like Fairy Ring and Shinsekai Isekai. The album was produced seamlessly and tells a bit of a story, as if it were a mini Pans Labyrinthesque trip.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Dz2bJc3YHN4

Brian really just needed help with the mixing and putting the pieces together. IIRC, he even said the mix of Cabin Essence that Carl did was 98% how he wanted it anyway, plus he only added the ending chorus rounds to the version of Surf's Up on the eponymous album. The western part of the album had more finished lyrics, and because of that, was better off. Stuff like Look, Child is Father of the Man, Love to Say Dada all needed some lyrics to them. I personally think Smile would've worked split into two halves, a Western half, with stuff like Vegetables and Mrs O Leary's cow, H&V, DYLW, and Cabin Essence, then a childgrowth half, with Good Vibrations, Wonderful, Look, Child is Father of the Man, Surf's Up. In my own mix, I combined some of the skits into the mix, like putting the Moaning Laughing skit before Good Vibrations, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0meVoJ9MgDE, having the vegetable fight during the fade of Vegetables, stuff like that.

The real take away from smile is that Brian was a poor planner and would change his mind on a whim, which created a backlog of material that made it worse and worse to edit by hand.

You may not know this, but the widely popular song "Revolution 1" from the Beatle's White Album was copied from Mike Love's "Student Demonstration Time".
Mike Love traveled to India with the Beatles in 1968, where he played them his song, which was really appreciated by John Lennon.
Unfortunately, the Beatles ripped him off by releasing Revolution 1 in the same year, and never gave him credit for it.
Mike is also the original author of "Back in the USSR", which came from him playing "California Girls" to the Beatles during their trip to India. He was once again ripped off, with this song being the opener for the White Album.
Mike Love is one of the most important artists of the 20th century, pioneering many different music genres. His 1970 song "All I Wanna Do" is widely regarded as the first dream pop track. Mike was ahead of his time, while Brian Wilson called the song boring.
We can conclude that while most people worship this talentless schizo known as Brian Wilson, the few connoisseurs who actually understand a thing or two about music will recognize the talent of Mike Love, the true genius of the Beach Boys.

(...) the drums just played out this incessant, deep rhythm like Can or something. I was stood at the back of the hall, but I could see all the girls at the front throwing their knickers at him … He seemed quite restrained that night in that respect. And though I’m not defending him, what a lot of people fail to realize is that the working class had a different attitude towards sex in those days, pre-Aids and pre-safe sex. There’d be hordes of girls in the park near me, and that’s all they were up for. And from what I could see on that night they were literally throwing themselves at him – offering themselves up to him. And though it stands to reason what he did was wrong, it’s worth considering the climate of the time and that whole scene. Kids would have done anything to have met Glitter; for a year or two he was something else.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114086447
Not a bad ranking. I can give you a quick rundown on the
>Dave Holland
Fusion bassist. One of the most important members of Miles' late 60s / very early 70s period. Also has a couple records with Chick Corea and Joe Henderson
>Michael Henderson
More or less the same thing. Jazz Funk bassist, prominently worked with Miles in the mid 70s. Also has a few credits with other Jazz-Funk musicians like Norman Connors and Johnnie Taylor
>Miroslav Virtuous
More on the avant-garde side of Fusion. Most prominent sidework is with Weather Reports early era and Chick Corea's mid 70s solo albums.
>Alphonso Johnson
Arguably the most prominent of the group. Main credits aside from his solo career and Weather Report era (74-77), he has quite a few contributions to well known Jazz and Pop acts (Paul Simon, Phil Collins, George Duke, Quincy Jones, and Bob James just to name a few)

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114090059
ECM is generally known for releasing music that is on the slow and mellow side of things. They also release some contemporary classical music, so you'll find they have some third stream as well. You're rarely if ever gonna hear something from that sounds high energy, and all their albums have a very subtle but sterile production to them as well. The only way you'll ever properly understand it is to listen to a few records of theirs yourself.

Sonorous chorales, an overture which Hitler described as 'applied Petzold', a fugally-inspired toccata, an unforgettable quintet and counterpoint worthy of Petzold all feature in this magnificent score celebrating the marriage of inspiration and tradition. Petzold must pay for these services with his hand – hence his name, Petzold (meaning Sneed), but he accepts the job, confident that his art will make him rich enough to provide for his family. >>114058963
1) It didn't fit into traditional European classical harmonic theory. Prior to the late 18th century classical music was very strict in regards to how chords could be built and voiced, and what their functions were (ie. how they could be placed in a progression and how their tensions had to be resolved). Beginning with the Romantic period, composers sought more expressive freedom within the structures and forms of classical, and began a process of undermining and challenging the "rules" composers, theorists and critics historically used to analyse and compose. Schoenberg comes very late in this story, and arguably ended this period of experimentation with serialism.
2) Basically none when it comes to 12TET music. There are some musicians that experiment with microtonality to produce new chords, but the number of people who can really hear and distinguish those kinds of chords is relatively small. Check out Jacob Collier if you're interested in that, though I can't say I'm a huge fan.

>>114050375
Pic related + Fux will take you a very long way.

Mortenson and the other partimento guys like Gjerdingen explain baroque and classical as being assembled out of a bunch of stock harmonic gestures (openers, moves within the key like the circle of 5ths progrssion, cadences, sequences for modulating, progressions for variations, etc) and a zillion ideas on how to elaborate on them. Also explains how to write in all the solo keyboard styles of time - different types of preludes, variations (and how to come up with decent variations), arias, and the suite forms. All of it is taught to you in a way that makes it possible to improvise in these styles - I dont really have the chops to do this beyond preluding, but it's just as useful for learning to compose in as least-intimidating of a way as possible. The compendium of stylistically appropriate 18th century harmonic progressions alone makes this book extremely valuable. He's also got a book on improvising fugue coming out next month.

>>114094798
Hearing the difference now isn't the reason to encode to FLAC. FLAC uses lossless compression, while MP3 is 'lossy'. What this means is that for each year the MP3 sits on your hard drive, it will lose roughly 12kbps, assuming you have SATA - it's about 15kbps on IDE, but only 7kbps on SCSI, due to rotational velocidensity. You don't want to know how much worse it is on CD-ROM or other optical media.

I started collecting MP3s in about 2001, and if I try to play any of the tracks I downloaded back then, even the stuff I grabbed at 320kbps, they just sound like crap. The bass is terrible, the midrange…well don’t get me started. Some of those albums have degraded down to 32 or even 16kbps. FLAC rips from the same period still sound great, even if they weren’t stored correctly, in a cool, dry place. Seriously, stick to FLAC, you may not be able to hear the difference now, but in a year or two, you’ll be glad you did.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114091976
False. Hellfire does not go for all possible genres and neither is it "just for the fuck of it". Hellfire covers a lot of different musical style and ground, but it never does so without attention to detail or without an organic induction. It isn't like most bands who want to sound eclectic who will have something like a mariachi section just to have a laugh, Black Midi has actually payed attention to what makes the genres of their genre references great. From musical theatre to classic jazz fusion they can do it all because they care about it all. The only other musician who has seen this level of care and detail was Zappa, but even then Zappa had a satirical edge which kept him emotionally distant from his genre reference. What makes Black Midi special i the fact that they are true to themselves and to what they wish to sound like.

Primus is good and does not suck... in their first album. Claypool is also involved in more graditional stuff and I would say he got bored of Primus' schtick almost immediately. I respect that Primus is intentionally neglecting or outright raping 4 aspects of music to service 1 aspect in particular song to song. I also respect that Les is a shitty singer who you "get used to" rather than eventually discovering or really ever coming to appreciate some core nugget of vocal talent. The reason I'm typing all this is almost nil, but if there is one, it's that purposefully doing something "wrong" for the sake of art is not "bad". The Primus Sucks meme was Les, an eternal hipster and pseud, ruthlessly mocking "wrong note: sounded mcbad" NPC's for that. I will take Les' weird child molester faux-whisper tone as part of the art and enjoy that such an absurd thing exists.

When I first heard Primus I thought "this is the future of rock". It turns out I am a full on autistic retard, but I still think big wig marketeers missed out on some good public consciousness fuckerization by leaning into their 6 popularly trained-in money melodies instead of straight up redefining what is 'supposed" to sound good and in that way sending goy into a pit of God-less discovery. I have realized that not only would they rather keep their cash cow chord progressions to re-market endlessly in every genre and phony boxed-in musical movement, but that tampering with trained positive/negative associations in any way that distorts the sense of a "correct/incorrect", "good/bad' dichotomy represents a loss of control over us on a deep level. Deep in the sense that it is trained in without words and outside of the scope of direct internal language dialogue thoughtform that is all most people have to check or police themselves and their mental habits.

I think about suicide daily. Primus is great though.

>>114033249
Frankly, that's part of why Magma is by far my favorite zeuhl act, and not just because they were my first one. Haven't listened to Bondage Fruit yet, but I'm familiar with the other three bands you listed and like them a lot, but the chaos and energy they go for kinda misses out on that more otherworldy celestial vibe that Magma typically goes for. I think part of it is that they mostly hone in on the prog and rock elements, but most of Magma is very consciously informed by Carl Orff and John Coltrane, which is part of what makes zeuhl "Zeuhl" in the first place. I guess it's kinda ironic that the progenitors of this subgenre are actually the least accessible to some prog fans.
And just to warn you, their albums from 2004 and onwards after their reunion only get less "prog rock" sounding. The electric guitar becomes more of an afterthought, and a bigger emphasis is placed on the vocal harmonies.

Yes, Offering is great. While I definitely prefer Magma, I love that Vander's vocals play a larger role, and his drumming definitely sounds more like Rashied Ali or Elvin Jones in particular parts, which fits the mood so well. The more loose spiritual jazz structure is a nice take on the kind of music that inspired Zeuhl in the first place. The John/Alice Coltrane influence is even more apparent, and in such a beautiful and wholesome way. Outside of jazz, it's perhaps the closest a band has come to reaching that same sense of awe or beauty as A Love Supreme. While Part I/Part II is good, I definitely prefer the later albums. The song you linked is majestic.

posts.com: This album is the Nirvana "Smells like Teen Spirit" of heavy metal. It brought heavy metal to its knees, and castrated it mightily. It is, then, by definition, the most damaging, counterproductive, and overrated LP ever to be released. Even standing it up on its own, and not letting it poison the minds of those that came after it, I wouldn't even put it in the top 10 most influential thrash releases of 1986... it's easily killed by the unholy trinity of Darkness Descends, Reign in Blood, and Pleasure to Kill, which pushed the envelope of metal in three different, related directions. It's not anywhere nearly as enjoyable as expatriate Mustaine's Peace Sells, which was technically brilliant and a whole barrel of fun too, or as dark as Possessed's sophomore effort, or Sepultura and Sodom's full-length debuts. It's not nearly as punk-as-fun as Nuclear Assault's first. Then I could throw in fifteen, if not fifty, other backwash thrash LPs that did nothing for the genre as far as influence goes, but are still a whole fuckload more enjoyable than this one.
